      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        GST and Property Sales in Queensland 2027: When Do Sellers Need to Charge GST?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Most home sellers will never deal with GST. But if your property is new, substantially renovated, or connected to a business, the rules change. Here is what you need to know before you list.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The majority of Queensland homeowners selling an established residential property will have nothing to do with GST. The general rule is straightforward: if you are a private individual selling a second-hand residential property, the sale is input-taxed and GST does not apply. You do not charge GST on the sale price and you do not need to be registered for GST to complete the transaction.</p>

      <p>That said, GST is an area where sellers regularly receive poor or incomplete information, particularly around new builds, substantially renovated properties, and properties with any commercial or business element. If any of those circumstances apply to you, it is worth understanding where the line sits before you have a contract on the table.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When GST does apply to a property sale</h2>
      <p>GST applies to a property sale in Queensland in four main situations. The first is the sale of new residential premises: a property that has not been previously sold as residential premises, or a property that has been substantially renovated (more on that distinction below). The second is the sale of commercial property or commercial residential premises such as hotels, serviced apartments, and student accommodation. The third is a sale made in the course or furtherance of an enterprise, which captures property developers, builders, and anyone who regularly acquires and sells property as part of a business. The fourth is a sale of a going concern, where a property is sold together with a rental business that qualifies as a going concern for GST purposes.</p>

      <p>For most owner-occupiers in Brisbane's inner east, none of these apply. You bought the house, lived in it or rented it out as an investment, and you are now selling it. That is a straightforward second-hand residential property sale and GST has no role in it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The renovation question</h2>
      <p>The area that trips up the most sellers is the concept of "new residential premises" as it applies to renovation. A property that has been renovated is not automatically treated as new for GST purposes. The Australian Taxation Office applies a "substantially renovated" test, which requires that the renovation be a substantial renovation of the building as a whole. Replacing a kitchen, repainting, updating bathrooms, or adding a deck does not make a property substantially renovated in the GST sense. A whole-of-house strip-out and rebuild that replaces most of the structural and non-structural components is a different matter.</p>

      <p>If you have undertaken a large-scale renovation, particularly one involving structural changes, new foundations, or near-total replacement of the internal fabric of the building, you should get tax advice before listing. The ATO has specific guidelines on what constitutes a substantial renovation, and getting this wrong has real consequences: if you are required to charge GST and you do not, you may still be liable for the tax amount out of your sale proceeds.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How GST affects the contract price</h2>
      <p>When GST does apply, the key question is whether the quoted price is inclusive or exclusive of GST. The contract must be clear. If the price is GST-inclusive, the buyer pays what is stated and the seller remits one-eleventh of the price to the ATO. If the price is stated as plus GST, the buyer pays more than the headline price. In residential transactions involving new builds by developers, it is standard practice to quote GST-inclusive prices, and buyers should assume this is the case. If the contract is silent on GST, the default position under the GST Act is that the price includes GST, which protects buyers from unexpected additional costs but reduces the effective net proceeds to the seller.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The margin scheme</h2>
      <p>The margin scheme is a GST concession that allows registered property developers and builders to calculate their GST liability on the margin between what they paid for the property and what they sell it for, rather than on the full sale price. This significantly reduces the GST payable on properties where the developer acquired the land before the current GST regime or at a low cost relative to the end sale price.</p>

      <p>The margin scheme is only available in specific circumstances and is not something that applies to a private individual selling an established home. For vendors selling a new residential property in a development context, the decision about whether to apply the margin scheme is one for your accountant or tax adviser, not your real estate agent.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Investment properties and home business use</h2>
      <p>Two scenarios that are less obvious but worth flagging: selling a property you have used partly for business, and selling a property that forms part of a larger enterprise.</p>

      <p>If you have claimed a portion of your home as a home office deduction and the proportion of business use has been significant, GST may be relevant to that proportion of the sale. Similarly, if you operate a short-term letting business through platforms such as Airbnb and have been running it as a GST-registered enterprise rather than as an incidental rental, the sale of the property may attract GST considerations that do not apply to a standard residential investment. The interaction between income tax, CGT, and GST on these properties is complicated, and getting professional advice before listing is the right approach rather than assuming the standard residential exemption applies.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should do before listing</h2>
      <p>For the large majority of Queensland homeowners, GST is simply not a consideration when selling. If you own an established residential property, have been using it as a home or a standard residential rental, and you are a private individual rather than a registered enterprise, your sale will not attract GST and you do not need to take any action on this front.</p>

      <p>If any of the following apply, get tax advice before you list: the property is a new build that has never been sold; you have undertaken major structural renovation works; you have been operating a business from the property or have claimed business use deductions against it; the property is commercial or has any commercial tenancy component; or you are registered for GST and the property is connected to your business assets. The cost of an hour with a tax adviser is negligible relative to the cost of getting it wrong in a property transaction.</p>

